/System/Volumes/Data/private/var is the writable Data-volume backing for /private/var on modern macOS.
What it contains:
1. System and app runtime data
2. Logs
3. Caches
4. Temporary files
5. Databases and state
6. VM/swap files
7. Per-user and per-service working directories
Common subpaths:
1. /private/var/log
2. /private/var/tmp
3. /private/var/folders
4. /private/var/db
5. /private/var/vm
Why the path looks like that:
1. macOS splits the OS into a read-only system volume and a writable data volume.
2. /System/Volumes/Data/... is the real on-disk location on the writable volume.
3. /private/var is the normal visible path in the merged filesystem view.
4. /var is typically a symlink to /private/var.
For indexing/scanning:
1. It is mostly system-managed, high-churn data.
2. It often contains transient files, sockets, locks, caches, and permission-sensitive content.
3. It is usually a good default skip unless you explicitly want system internals.
